BqySpT53xDj-xTC2Kqkq2dKkZNVQk0REXOdn80vaiM7sn-Io6RWO0a4RlFa5j-2zuAyHcyq-JUP_ULKPOxUBGa1XooZsP_GvCAl7QWZWtTu9F3G4YSYJdVrieMC8sA1zDyMezzcZTaT2LkNxjj_DHd8dJajS-DZuB032wapdMB-qrkJ2USZs2nDufnO2PAfIWtazOguOWekJvkinctU2imb89mHdIaPOxKNslmdGUT6pQ8oyaQPPFExtBCJO\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating dynamic coverage issues**\\n\\nI'm exploring issues with dynamic coverage tracks in a Doobie test class. The previous attempt might not have compiled or run due to an invalid result.swap.getOrElse. I wonder if the left type as Unit creates problems when expected to be Throwable. Another thought is that the native image could lack reflection metadata for `java.lang.String`. Even though `Class.forName` on existing classes should work, it seems there’s a possibility it didn’t get recorded due to failed reflection calls. Should I use a real JDBC driver since Doobie core doesn't include H2?\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring test dependency options**\\n\\nI’m considering adding a test dependency since the rules don’t forbid it. It might be beneficial to create a better public API using `fromDriverManager` with the driver \\\"org.h2.Driver\\\" and the URL \\\"jdbc:h2:mem:...\\\". I could also add `testImplementation com.h2database:h2`, but my focus should be on the active class. H2’s native image compatibility intrigues me, especially concerning metadata and dynamic class loading. It might be simpler to implement our own `java.sql.Driver` as a test source. I wonder if `Class.forName` needs metadata for the test driver class to succeed.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying the driver initialization process**\\n\\nI can explicitly reference the class to ensure it gets included, but the method call still needs to be dynamic. I need to make sure that `DriverManager` can return a connection if the driver is registered successfully. To avoid requiring a real connection, I could use a custom driver that's registered via the class's static initialization. However, using Scala's companion object for static initialization could be tricky. It seems that calling `Class.forName(driver)` should initialize and register the driver appropriately.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_RJa17QdwB4JG9mgTAfvf44SW|fc_07804db651c470730169fafaf01cc08193a8975196177b2c65", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.tpolecat/doobie-core_3/0.13.4/src/test/scala/org_tpolecat/doobie_core_3/TransactorInnerTransactorInnerFromDriverManagerTest.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.sql.SQLException\nimport scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext\n\nclass TransactorInnerTransactorInnerFromDriverManagerTest {\n  private implicit val contextShift: ContextShift[IO] = IO.contextShift(ExecutionContext.global)\n  private val blocker: Blocker = Blocker.liftExecutionContext(ExecutionContext.global)\n\n  @Test\n  @Timeout(10)\n  def fromDriverManagerLoadsDriverClassWhenOpeningConnection(): Unit = {\n    val xa: Transactor.Aux[IO, Unit] =\n      Transactor.fromDriverManager[IO](\n        \"java.lang.String\",\n        \"jdbc:doobie-core-test:missing-database\",\n        blocker\n      )\n\n    val result: Either[Throwable, Unit] =\n      xa.connect(xa.kernel).use(_ => IO.unit).attempt.unsafeRunSync()\n\n    val failure: Throwable =\n      result.swap.getOrElse(new AssertionError(\"Expected connection acquisition to fail\"))\n\n    assertThat(failure).isInstanceOf(classOf[SQLException])\n    assertThat(failure.getMessage).contains(\"No suitable driver\")\n  }\n}\n", "newText": "import java.sql.Connection\nimport java.sql.Driver\nimport java.sql.DriverManager\nimport java.sql.DriverPropertyInfo\nimport java.sql.SQLException\nimport java.util.Properties\nimport java.util.logging.Logger\nimport scala.concurrent.ExecutionContext\n\nclass TransactorInnerTransactorInnerFromDriverManagerTest {\n  private implicit val contextShift: ContextShift[IO] = IO.contextShift(ExecutionContext.global)\n  private val blocker: Blocker = Blocker.liftExecutionContext(ExecutionContext.global)\n\n  @Test\n  @Timeout(10)\n  def fromDriverManagerLoadsDriverClassWhenOpeningConnection(): Unit = {\n    val driver: DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver = new DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver\n    DriverManager.registerDriver(driver)\n    try {\n      val xa: Transactor.Aux[IO, Unit] =\n        Transactor.fromDriverManager[IO](\n          classOf[DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver].getName,\n          DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver.url,\n          blocker\n        )\n\n      val result: Either[Throwable, Unit] =\n        xa.connect(xa.kernel).use(_ => IO.unit).attempt.unsafeRunSync()\n\n      val failure: Throwable =\n        result.swap.getOrElse(new AssertionError(\"Expected connection acquisition to fail\"))\n\n      assertThat(failure).isInstanceOf(classOf[SQLException])\n      assertThat(failure.getMessage).contains(DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver.failureMessage)\n    } finally {\n      DriverManager.deregisterDriver(driver)\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nobject DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver {\n  val url: String = \"jdbc:doobie-core-from-driver-manager-test\"\n  val failureMessage: String = \"driver was loaded and asked to connect\"\n}\n\nclass DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver extends Driver {\n  override def connect(url: String, info: Properties): Connection = {\n    if (acceptsURL(url)) {\n      throw new SQLException(DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver.failureMessage)\n    }\n    null\n  }\n\n  override def acceptsURL(url: String): Boolean =\n    DoobieCoreFromDriverManagerFailingDriver.url == url\n\n  override def getPropertyInfo(url: String, info: Properties): Array[DriverPropertyInfo] =\n    Array.empty[DriverPropertyInfo]\n\n  override def getMajorVersion: Int = 1\n\n  override def getMinorVersion: Int = 0\n\n  override def jdbcCompliant(): Boolean = false\n\n  override def getParentLogger: Logger = Logger.getGlobal\n}\n"}]}}], "api": "openai-responses